		<td colspan=2 class="msg_text_cell" width="100%" valign=top style="text-align: justify; 
		" 
			>
			Someone said something about having a timing feature to prevent repeat task abuse. Are you aware that such a thing is already in place? Specifically, you cannot request a second "short" task for at least 30 minutes after the start of the first one. I learned this with my wizard, who kept getting nothing but short exploration tasks from the OT taskmaster. He'd knock the task out in 10-15 minutes, and still have another 15-20 minutes on his timer before he could request a new task. Thus, at level 62, he could earn at most about 8.5% AA every 30 minutes doing tasks. I presume that is the rate of XP gain they are looking for.<br><br>I would like to see some task tuning. In particular, if you get a kill 10 of mob X and collect 4 of piece Y quest, please make sure that 10 of mob X actually has a reasonable chance of dropping 4 piece Y's. I've only done two of these, because both times I had finished the 10 of X part without seeing a single Y drop. (Yes, this has been /bug'ed in both cases.)<br><br>Tradeskill tasks would be awesome. Even better if they were somehow attuned to your skill level, but that would be really tricky to balance. One would think that my 248 brewer who is a 27 druid should NOT get the same XP for a brewing task that my 65 bard/200 brewer might get. But it would be fun to do a task challenging for a 248 brewer that was still doable at level 27. Probably dreaming a bit here.
								<p><div style="width: 100%; height: 120; overflow: hidden;">
								
							<IMG SRC="http://mosa.unity.ncsu.edu/EQ/combined522.jpg" WIDTH=522 HEIGHT=89>
							</div>
								
