			<BR>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<HR>
Traevanon wrote:<BR>
<DIV>
<DIV>
<HR>
noone ever suggested someone get normal ldon adventure points for completeltion of the task. The fact that it wold be scaled is assumed.</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>if it takes five or six task or even ten task to achieve the same points as a succesful ldon adventure. then you have what was suggested</DIV>
<DIV>A viable reward for completing task and more incentive to do ldons. basically it would take four or five hours&nbsp; to get the same amount of points for a succesful 30 minute ldon adventure.</DIV>
<DIV>
<HR>
</DIV></DIV>
<P>Even scaled you still have ACCESS to the same things that a group can gain.&nbsp;&nbsp;I cant agree with equating&nbsp;killing 40 first level kobolds to killing&nbsp;one 40th level creature.&nbsp; Its a simplification, but it illustrates the concept.&nbsp; A 20th level solo quest, repeated 1485 times (one point each) is still not worth rewarding with a piece of top level LDoN gear.</P>
<P>The only things you dont gain access to are the actual&nbsp;dungeon drops.
<HR>
</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>My thoughts, when I made that suggestion, was that the task would require something from within the dungeon, and not just one, but multiple ones.&nbsp; I&nbsp;would&nbsp;think that completing a dungeon would be required somewhere in the task.&nbsp; Longer tasks may want you to get something from two or three different ones.&nbsp; I don't think it's acceptable to say, kill 10 zelniaks in DSP, collect 4 zelniak meats and turn them in to some dude would give you LDoN points, even if it's only a couple.&nbsp; Now, killing 10 zelniaks in DSP, collecting 4 zelniak meats, and then baking&nbsp;them into zelniak meat pies, with a no drop item from one of the dungeons before turning them in would be better.</P>
<P>&nbsp;</P>
